WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.914 --> 00:00:07.330
SPEAKER 1: Well,
welcome everyone.

00:00:07.330 --> 00:00:09.810
We're excited to
have everyone here

00:00:09.810 --> 00:00:12.100
to hear-- to speak with
William Paul Young.

00:00:12.100 --> 00:00:15.240
Part of trying to organize
these talks to people that

00:00:15.240 --> 00:00:19.770
can talk on issues for answers
that Google doesn't have

00:00:19.770 --> 00:00:21.050
answers for.

00:00:21.050 --> 00:00:24.060
And so we're excited to have
William Paul, that certainly

00:00:24.060 --> 00:00:27.060
has opened up a lot of questions
with his book "The Shack."

00:00:27.060 --> 00:00:28.957
So it was released
over 10 years ago

00:00:28.957 --> 00:00:30.540
and has become one
of the best selling

00:00:30.540 --> 00:00:32.580
books of the 21st century.

00:00:32.580 --> 00:00:35.590
It was actually recently
made into a film,

00:00:35.590 --> 00:00:36.716
which Google is very proud.

00:00:36.716 --> 00:00:38.840
We were one of the first
to have electronic rights,

00:00:38.840 --> 00:00:40.260
so it was released
just this week

00:00:40.260 --> 00:00:42.360
on Google Play and YouTube.

00:00:42.360 --> 00:00:44.760
So for those who have
not read the book,

00:00:44.760 --> 00:00:45.930
we have free copies today.

00:00:45.930 --> 00:00:48.360
You can actually watch
the movie as well.

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:51.010
Paul is actually the
author of many other books,

00:00:51.010 --> 00:00:54.810
including "Eve," "Crossroads,"
and the recently released

00:00:54.810 --> 00:00:56.850
"Lies We Believe About God."

00:00:56.850 --> 00:01:00.000
So for any other questions,
please Google his name.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.790
There's plenty out there, but
I will give plenty of time

00:01:02.790 --> 00:01:06.164
because he has a lot
to share with us today.

00:01:06.164 --> 00:01:09.601
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:13.012 --> 00:01:14.470
WILLIAM PAUL YOUNG:
Good afternoon.

00:01:14.470 --> 00:01:17.680
Just barely, but it's so
good to be here at Apple.

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:18.490
I'm just kidding.

00:01:21.160 --> 00:01:25.690
I figured with a
minimalist stage--

00:01:25.690 --> 00:01:26.890
I'm just saying.

00:01:26.890 --> 00:01:30.940
So let me tell you a
little bit about who I am

00:01:30.940 --> 00:01:34.210
and what my background is.

00:01:34.210 --> 00:01:36.240
I'm married to Kim.

00:01:36.240 --> 00:01:38.517
It will be 38
years in September.

00:01:41.790 --> 00:01:45.180
I have-- we have six children.

00:01:45.180 --> 00:01:49.740
Our age range is 23 to 36.

00:01:49.740 --> 00:01:52.980
We have our 10th
grandbaby on the way.

00:01:52.980 --> 00:01:55.470
They're all nine
years old and under,

00:01:55.470 --> 00:02:00.577
and that's the best
thing I've ever done,

00:02:00.577 --> 00:02:02.410
being married and having
children and having

00:02:02.410 --> 00:02:03.310
grandchildren.

00:02:06.010 --> 00:02:08.590
My background, which
I thought was normal

00:02:08.590 --> 00:02:12.370
until I left the world
that I grew up in--

00:02:12.370 --> 00:02:14.742
I'm a missionary kid,
third culture kid.

00:02:14.742 --> 00:02:16.450
I grew up in the
highlands of New Guinea.

00:02:16.450 --> 00:02:20.500
My parents were missionaries,
pioneer missionaries,

00:02:20.500 --> 00:02:23.440
Protestant, fundamentalist,
evangelical.

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:26.880
And I was a year old when
we moved into the highlands.

00:02:26.880 --> 00:02:28.255
So I grew up in
a tribal culture.

00:02:31.900 --> 00:02:33.800
New Guinea is very unusual.

00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:38.080
It has over 800 unrelated
language groups.

00:02:38.080 --> 00:02:40.570
And our tribe was one
of the bigger ones--

00:02:40.570 --> 00:02:44.140
40,000 to 60,000 people
over 100 square miles.

00:02:44.140 --> 00:02:48.070
But their language
had never been

00:02:48.070 --> 00:02:50.380
heard outside of their culture.

00:02:50.380 --> 00:02:55.780
And going in as a year old,
it became my first language

00:02:55.780 --> 00:02:59.620
and my first dreaming language.

00:02:59.620 --> 00:03:00.830
It was my language.

00:03:00.830 --> 00:03:03.070
And when I was five
years old, Wycliffe

00:03:03.070 --> 00:03:05.080
came in to translate
the language,

00:03:05.080 --> 00:03:08.170
and I was the
informant because I'm

00:03:08.170 --> 00:03:10.855
the only one that could
speak it fluently, Ndani--

00:03:10.855 --> 00:03:13.600
and Ndani is a
dialect-- and English.

00:03:13.600 --> 00:03:18.920
So sent to boarding
school when I was six.

00:03:18.920 --> 00:03:22.810
I had some really great
advantages growing up

00:03:22.810 --> 00:03:25.040
in a multicultural world.

00:03:25.040 --> 00:03:28.330
It gave me an ability to
look from outside the box.

00:03:28.330 --> 00:03:29.650
I think that was a great gift.

00:03:29.650 --> 00:03:35.050
It gave me a facility to
move in and out of culture,

00:03:35.050 --> 00:03:40.630
but it left some really deep
losses at the same time.

00:03:40.630 --> 00:03:42.640
Part of it was the
way that I grew up.

00:03:42.640 --> 00:03:45.730
I had a very angry
young man father

00:03:45.730 --> 00:03:48.040
who didn't have a
chip for being a dad,

00:03:48.040 --> 00:03:54.610
and so he was an
abusive disciplinarian.

00:03:54.610 --> 00:03:57.070
And it took me, in
terms of my journey,

00:03:57.070 --> 00:03:58.900
so that you have
a sense of this--

00:03:58.900 --> 00:04:02.020
it took me 50 years to
wipe the face of my father

00:04:02.020 --> 00:04:02.920
off the face of God.

00:04:05.560 --> 00:04:07.840
And then the second
great sadness

00:04:07.840 --> 00:04:09.520
that I had was the
sexual abuse that

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:14.140
started in the tribal culture
and that then continued

00:04:14.140 --> 00:04:15.640
in missionary boarding school.

00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:19.660
The big boys would molest
the little boys at night,

00:04:19.660 --> 00:04:23.170
and so that kind of tore the
fabric of my soul to shreds.

00:04:23.170 --> 00:04:25.960
And then the issue of belonging
that a lot of third culture

00:04:25.960 --> 00:04:27.550
kids have.

00:04:27.550 --> 00:04:29.500
If we don't find
someone to belong to,

00:04:29.500 --> 00:04:31.060
we never belong anywhere.

00:04:31.060 --> 00:04:33.910
It's not a geography anymore.

00:04:33.910 --> 00:04:36.821
And so as a first-born
missionary kid,

00:04:36.821 --> 00:04:39.070
preacher's kid-- because
when we came back to Canada--

00:04:39.070 --> 00:04:41.810
I was born in Canada--

00:04:41.810 --> 00:04:44.830
my father was an itinerant
pastor, and we moved a lot.

00:04:44.830 --> 00:04:48.550
I went to 13 schools before
I graduated high school.

00:04:48.550 --> 00:04:54.460
And I became a performer,
first-born performer.

00:04:54.460 --> 00:04:59.680
And at the same time, I'm on
a journey of spirituality,

00:04:59.680 --> 00:05:02.740
trying to figure out
my roots, being based

00:05:02.740 --> 00:05:06.770
in evangelical Christianity.

00:05:06.770 --> 00:05:08.740
And I'm lost in my head.

00:05:08.740 --> 00:05:11.230
I became an intellectual
rationalist,

00:05:11.230 --> 00:05:14.540
because that's the only safe
place that I could find.

00:05:14.540 --> 00:05:18.920
Because everything below
the neck was pretty broken.

00:05:18.920 --> 00:05:23.100
And I functioned by trying
to live from the outside in.

00:05:23.100 --> 00:05:26.440
So "The Shack," in a sense,
besides just being a story,

00:05:26.440 --> 00:05:29.470
becomes a metaphor,
becomes a parable.

00:05:29.470 --> 00:05:33.730
And the shack
itself, on one level,

00:05:33.730 --> 00:05:37.260
is the house on the inside
that people help us build.

00:05:37.260 --> 00:05:39.670
And a lot of us, we
didn't get good help,

00:05:39.670 --> 00:05:41.510
and so it becomes
a broken place.

00:05:41.510 --> 00:05:43.360
It's our own soul.

00:05:43.360 --> 00:05:45.730
It's the broken heart
of a human being,

00:05:45.730 --> 00:05:48.790
and it becomes a place we
store all of our addictions

00:05:48.790 --> 00:05:50.200
and we hide all of our secrets.

00:05:50.200 --> 00:05:52.300
And we never want to
invade another human being

00:05:52.300 --> 00:05:57.040
into that place because we're
terrified that if we do they

00:05:57.040 --> 00:05:59.360
will hate us as much as we do.

00:05:59.360 --> 00:06:00.790
And so we become a performer.

00:06:00.790 --> 00:06:03.460
We set up something
outside, a facade

00:06:03.460 --> 00:06:05.770
that we can paint as
fast as we can pick up

00:06:05.770 --> 00:06:08.080
people's expectations.

00:06:08.080 --> 00:06:15.460
And that became the
metaphor for my own heart.

00:06:15.460 --> 00:06:17.922
I've always been a
writer, like anybody does.

00:06:17.922 --> 00:06:19.630
You know, you write
stuff and you give it

00:06:19.630 --> 00:06:20.830
to your friends and
family, and they

00:06:20.830 --> 00:06:22.413
think it's the best
thing in the world

00:06:22.413 --> 00:06:25.330
because they're your
friends or family.

00:06:25.330 --> 00:06:28.360
And I had written gifts over the
years for friends and family.

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:32.880
And Kim, my wife, had been
saying for about four years,

00:06:32.880 --> 00:06:34.720
Someday, as a gift
for our children,

00:06:34.720 --> 00:06:37.300
would you write something
that puts in one place

00:06:37.300 --> 00:06:39.040
how you think?

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:41.800
Because you think
outside the box.

00:06:41.800 --> 00:06:44.650
And I didn't feel healthy
enough to do that.

00:06:44.650 --> 00:06:46.162
I didn't know what that was.

00:06:46.162 --> 00:06:47.620
She didn't, either,
and by the way,

00:06:47.620 --> 00:06:50.307
when the book eventually
got printed, she said to me,

00:06:50.307 --> 00:06:51.890
you know, when I
asked you to do this,

00:06:51.890 --> 00:06:53.473
I was thinking like
four to six pages.

00:06:56.810 --> 00:06:59.920
But I love story,
and story has a way

00:06:59.920 --> 00:07:03.790
of sneaking past our watchful
dragons, as Lewis would say.

00:07:03.790 --> 00:07:07.030
And story-- we have
an affinity for it,

00:07:07.030 --> 00:07:09.760
because every single
human being is a story.

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:13.360
And so I wanted to
write them a story.

00:07:13.360 --> 00:07:15.520
And the year I
turned 50, I finally

00:07:15.520 --> 00:07:18.520
felt healthy enough
to do it, and I

00:07:18.520 --> 00:07:21.830
did it mostly on the train
to one of my three jobs.

00:07:21.830 --> 00:07:22.900
I was working three jobs.

00:07:22.900 --> 00:07:25.570
I was doing shipping and
receiving for a circuit board

00:07:25.570 --> 00:07:26.800
manufacturing company.

00:07:26.800 --> 00:07:28.840
I did all the
janitorial, so I did

00:07:28.840 --> 00:07:31.390
all the toilets and the floors.

00:07:31.390 --> 00:07:34.960
And then I was a hotel night
clerk on the side part-time,

00:07:34.960 --> 00:07:38.410
and part-time was doing web
conferencing on the web.

00:07:38.410 --> 00:07:44.040
And then I worked on a hotline
in a food processing company.

00:07:44.040 --> 00:07:50.680
And the year before
I wrote the story,

00:07:50.680 --> 00:07:55.570
was the 11th year of a
dismantling and rebuilding

00:07:55.570 --> 00:07:59.230
process that is represented
by Mackenzie's weekend

00:07:59.230 --> 00:08:00.520
in the shack.

00:08:00.520 --> 00:08:03.850
In the book, Mackenzie
is the main character.

00:08:03.850 --> 00:08:05.525
People ask me, is
this a true story?

00:08:05.525 --> 00:08:06.900
And I tell them,
yeah, it's true.

00:08:06.900 --> 00:08:08.110
It's just not real.

00:08:08.110 --> 00:08:13.150
Like all parables-- they're all
true, they're just not real.

00:08:13.150 --> 00:08:18.850
And I wrote this as a story
to communicate to my children.

00:08:18.850 --> 00:08:20.540
I wrote it for
them for Christmas.

00:08:20.540 --> 00:08:24.190
That's the whole goal, was
to get it done for Christmas.

00:08:24.190 --> 00:08:29.789
At Christmas, I made 15
copies at Office Depot.

00:08:29.789 --> 00:08:32.289
And I like to tell people there
are two things that you need

00:08:32.289 --> 00:08:34.630
to understand about
this whole crazy thing

00:08:34.630 --> 00:08:36.590
that I'm in the middle of.

00:08:36.590 --> 00:08:41.659
Those 15 copies did everything
I ever wanted that book to do.

00:08:41.659 --> 00:08:45.650
I had never-- it never once
crossed my mind to publish it.

00:08:45.650 --> 00:08:47.780
I mean, that's not my world.

00:08:47.780 --> 00:08:50.090
I didn't know anything
about it, and it just

00:08:50.090 --> 00:08:52.040
wasn't on my bucket
list or anything else.

00:08:52.040 --> 00:08:54.470
I wrote this as a
gift for my children,

00:08:54.470 --> 00:08:58.550
trying to say, let me tell
you about the God who actually

00:08:58.550 --> 00:09:02.960
showed up and healed my heart,
not the God I grew up with.

00:09:02.960 --> 00:09:05.279
That's why when Papa God
comes through the door,

00:09:05.279 --> 00:09:07.070
he doesn't come through
the door as Gandalf

00:09:07.070 --> 00:09:09.470
with a bad attitude--

00:09:09.470 --> 00:09:11.990
white-bearded,
distant, grandfatherly,

00:09:11.990 --> 00:09:13.092
that whole thing.

00:09:13.092 --> 00:09:15.050
Because I'm trying to
get as far away from that

00:09:15.050 --> 00:09:17.250
imagery as possible.

00:09:17.250 --> 00:09:18.770
And the other
thing I tell people

00:09:18.770 --> 00:09:23.480
is that you need to know that
everything that matters to me

00:09:23.480 --> 00:09:26.360
was in place before
I wrote the book--

00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:29.120
identity, worth, value,
significance, security,

00:09:29.120 --> 00:09:32.330
meaning, purpose, destiny,
community, and love.

00:09:32.330 --> 00:09:35.820
They were all in place
before I wrote the book.

00:09:35.820 --> 00:09:40.680
And I'm so grateful for
that, because a lot of times

00:09:40.680 --> 00:09:43.590
if those things are not
in place, you use work

00:09:43.590 --> 00:09:45.750
or you use creativity
or you use whatever

00:09:45.750 --> 00:09:49.170
to gain identity, worth,
value, significance, security,

00:09:49.170 --> 00:09:51.309
meaning, purpose, destiny,
community, and love.

00:09:51.309 --> 00:09:53.850
And then you start to suck the
life out of your relationships

00:09:53.850 --> 00:09:56.550
and the people around you.

00:09:56.550 --> 00:09:59.220
And all of those
things were in place.

00:09:59.220 --> 00:10:02.280
The book didn't add any
of those things to me.

00:10:02.280 --> 00:10:08.730
What it gave me as a gift, which
I will be forever grateful for,

00:10:08.730 --> 00:10:11.130
is an invitation
into the holy ground

00:10:11.130 --> 00:10:14.650
of other people's stories.

00:10:14.650 --> 00:10:19.300
Let me give you an example,
and I'll do it from the movie.

00:10:19.300 --> 00:10:22.660
I didn't anticipate being
involved in the film.

00:10:22.660 --> 00:10:25.570
When I laid the rights down,
I laid them down 100%--

00:10:25.570 --> 00:10:31.870
no creative control,
no rights, period.

00:10:31.870 --> 00:10:35.410
Which was fine-- in the
course of how this unfolded,

00:10:35.410 --> 00:10:37.750
it worked, and it
was fine by me.

00:10:37.750 --> 00:10:40.460
So I did not anticipate
being involved.

00:10:40.460 --> 00:10:45.220
Lionsgate called me up and
said, would you come talk to us?

00:10:45.220 --> 00:10:48.700
I think they were
partly checking me out

00:10:48.700 --> 00:10:53.180
to see if I would be an
enemy of the project,

00:10:53.180 --> 00:10:55.120
but I don't know that for sure.

00:10:55.120 --> 00:10:58.120
But we didn't end up talking
about the movie or business

00:10:58.120 --> 00:10:59.110
or anything.

00:10:59.110 --> 00:11:03.310
All we did is told
stories and cried a lot,

00:11:03.310 --> 00:11:07.150
because everybody in this
room, everybody in humanity,

00:11:07.150 --> 00:11:10.690
knows about love and
knows about loss.

00:11:10.690 --> 00:11:12.520
All of our divisions,
politically,

00:11:12.520 --> 00:11:16.670
ethnically, all of that,
we do have these things

00:11:16.670 --> 00:11:18.800
in common, love and loss.

00:11:18.800 --> 00:11:23.810
And the book is a human
story about loss and love.

00:11:23.810 --> 00:11:26.772
And so it was great.

00:11:26.772 --> 00:11:27.980
I had a great time with them.

00:11:27.980 --> 00:11:34.490
Well, a number of months later,
I get a call from Gil Netter.

00:11:34.490 --> 00:11:36.740
He was the producer for "Life
of Pi," "Marley and Me,"

00:11:36.740 --> 00:11:38.960
"Blind Side," and
20 other movies,

00:11:38.960 --> 00:11:41.210
and he was the producer
for "The Shack."

00:11:41.210 --> 00:11:45.950
And he said, would you
please look at the script

00:11:45.950 --> 00:11:48.140
and give us your feedback?

00:11:48.140 --> 00:11:49.220
Sure.

00:11:49.220 --> 00:11:50.490
So I was able to do that.

00:11:50.490 --> 00:11:54.140
Then they said, what do you
think about these actors?

00:11:54.140 --> 00:11:56.270
And so that was part
of the conversation.

00:11:56.270 --> 00:11:59.720
Not any of it did they have to
take seriously, you understand,

00:11:59.720 --> 00:12:02.580
because I had no creative
control, no rights.

00:12:02.580 --> 00:12:06.400
They said, well,
would you come--

00:12:06.400 --> 00:12:09.470
Lionsgate calls me
and says, would you

00:12:09.470 --> 00:12:11.720
consider coming on
the first day's shoot

00:12:11.720 --> 00:12:15.730
and praying a blessing over
the entire cast and crew?

00:12:15.730 --> 00:12:17.110
Yeah.

00:12:17.110 --> 00:12:18.725
So I did.

00:12:18.725 --> 00:12:21.100
So the first day I'm on the
set, and they shot most of it

00:12:21.100 --> 00:12:22.760
in British Columbia.

00:12:22.760 --> 00:12:29.067
And so I'm on the set, and
I mean, it's so surreal.

00:12:29.067 --> 00:12:31.150
You write a story for your
kids, and it's becoming

00:12:31.150 --> 00:12:32.110
a major motion picture.

00:12:32.110 --> 00:12:35.000
And there are, like, 60
people being paid to do this.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:37.141
It is the weirdest thing ever.

00:12:37.141 --> 00:12:39.640
And at the end of the day, I'm
just standing there watching.

00:12:39.640 --> 00:12:46.570
And Gil Netter yells, hey,
Paul, you want to be in a cameo?

00:12:46.570 --> 00:12:48.457
I said, like in the movie?

00:12:48.457 --> 00:12:49.040
He says, yeah.

00:12:49.040 --> 00:12:51.630
He says, I've never shot a movie
where the author was alive,

00:12:51.630 --> 00:12:58.110
a book adaptation that I
didn't put the author in it.

00:12:58.110 --> 00:12:59.800
I said, sure, my kids
are going to love

00:12:59.800 --> 00:13:01.120
this, what do I have to do?

00:13:01.120 --> 00:13:04.450
He says, all you have to do
is walk through this scene.

00:13:04.450 --> 00:13:07.470
Well, I've walked
most of my life.

00:13:07.470 --> 00:13:09.640
How hard can this be, right?

00:13:09.640 --> 00:13:13.330
And it only took five takes.

00:13:13.330 --> 00:13:15.930
Because you don't think
about walking when you walk.

00:13:15.930 --> 00:13:17.657
It's like, oh.

00:13:17.657 --> 00:13:19.240
So he was like, oh,
let's do it again,

00:13:19.240 --> 00:13:21.640
this time slow down a little
bit, don't photo bomb--

00:13:21.640 --> 00:13:22.900
whatever.

00:13:22.900 --> 00:13:25.450
And so you'll have
to look for it.

00:13:25.450 --> 00:13:26.710
It's all of two seconds.

00:13:26.710 --> 00:13:31.030
But just look for kind of
a short, elderly, balding,

00:13:31.030 --> 00:13:36.480
overweight white guy who
just walks through the scene.

00:13:36.480 --> 00:13:38.140
But it was just incredible.

00:13:38.140 --> 00:13:43.540
Well, a few months later, I
get a call, and they said,

00:13:43.540 --> 00:13:46.160
would you consider
coming back on the set?

00:13:46.160 --> 00:13:49.050
And they were near the
end of their shoot.

00:13:49.050 --> 00:13:50.300
It was like 60 days.

00:13:50.300 --> 00:13:52.400
And if you know
anything about movies--

00:13:52.400 --> 00:13:56.150
which I didn't but it's
a great learning curve--

00:13:56.150 --> 00:13:59.870
they have multiple
locations being shot.

00:13:59.870 --> 00:14:02.150
And they're all out of
order, depending on when

00:14:02.150 --> 00:14:03.260
the actors are available.

00:14:03.260 --> 00:14:06.000
So sometimes the
actors are available.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.396
And so the first day shoot,
in fact, was the scene--

00:14:09.396 --> 00:14:11.270
and the one that I walk
through, is the scene

00:14:11.270 --> 00:14:15.290
when Willie, played by Tim
McGraw, and Sam Worthington,

00:14:15.290 --> 00:14:16.790
played by Mackenzie--
they're having

00:14:16.790 --> 00:14:19.220
a conversation as the kids
are being piled into the car

00:14:19.220 --> 00:14:21.100
to go camping.

00:14:21.100 --> 00:14:25.400
And this is the one
where Tim walks over,

00:14:25.400 --> 00:14:28.400
and the scene begins with
him saying he's got a dog.

00:14:28.400 --> 00:14:30.770
And he says,
summer's last hurrah.

00:14:30.770 --> 00:14:32.280
That's the first line.

00:14:32.280 --> 00:14:34.790
And in that scene, there's
a shot right at Tim McGraw,

00:14:34.790 --> 00:14:37.040
and that's when you'll see
me walk through that scene.

00:14:40.790 --> 00:14:44.150
But on that day, Octavia
Spencer, who plays Papa,

00:14:44.150 --> 00:14:46.780
was not there, nor Graham
Greene, who also plays Papa.

00:14:49.670 --> 00:14:51.920
But Aviv wasn't there,
who plays Jesus,

00:14:51.920 --> 00:14:55.474
and Sumi, who plays the
Holy Spirit, wasn't there.

00:14:55.474 --> 00:14:57.890
So the first day's shoot, the
Father, Son, and Holy Spirit

00:14:57.890 --> 00:15:02.880
are absent, at least
in any visible sense.

00:15:02.880 --> 00:15:07.266
So later, 60 days later,
I get a call saying,

00:15:07.266 --> 00:15:09.890
we're near the end of the shoot,
would you consider coming back

00:15:09.890 --> 00:15:12.110
on the set for another day?

00:15:12.110 --> 00:15:13.960
And I said, sure.

00:15:13.960 --> 00:15:15.710
They said, here's what
we're going to do.

00:15:15.710 --> 00:15:21.440
Wednesday, we're going to
fly you up to Vancouver, BC,

00:15:21.440 --> 00:15:25.325
and then transport will take you
to a hotel in Chilliwack, which

00:15:25.325 --> 00:15:27.200
is about two and a half
hours from Vancouver,

00:15:27.200 --> 00:15:28.430
depending on traffic.

00:15:28.430 --> 00:15:29.810
And it's in the valley.

00:15:29.810 --> 00:15:34.220
And then that night, Wednesday
night, you'll get a call sheet

00:15:34.220 --> 00:15:36.440
that will tell you when
we're picking you up Thursday

00:15:36.440 --> 00:15:39.140
and where we're taking you.

00:15:39.140 --> 00:15:41.270
And then you'll spend all
day Thursday on the set.

00:15:41.270 --> 00:15:46.490
Friday, transport will take you
back to Vancouver to fly out.

00:15:46.490 --> 00:15:48.300
Simple.

00:15:48.300 --> 00:15:49.800
This is great.

00:15:49.800 --> 00:15:53.040
Well, I'm thinking about this
as I'm sitting at my desk

00:15:53.040 --> 00:15:55.750
after we've got this all set up.

00:15:55.750 --> 00:15:56.900
And I think, you know what?

00:15:56.900 --> 00:15:58.890
There's a guy I've
been trying to meet

00:15:58.890 --> 00:16:02.100
who lives in Abbotsford,
which is right next door

00:16:02.100 --> 00:16:04.440
to Chilliwack,
where my hotel is.

00:16:04.440 --> 00:16:05.867
And I've been
trying to meet him.

00:16:05.867 --> 00:16:07.700
I had a lot of email
conversations with him.

00:16:07.700 --> 00:16:10.080
He's a theologian
named Brad Jersak.

00:16:10.080 --> 00:16:12.390
And in fact, I'd endorse
his last book, which

00:16:12.390 --> 00:16:16.020
is "A More Christlike God."

00:16:16.020 --> 00:16:18.480
And he'd read "Eve"
and was all over it.

00:16:18.480 --> 00:16:20.360
He's a patristic theologian.

00:16:20.360 --> 00:16:23.700
And so we'd had all
these conversations.

00:16:23.700 --> 00:16:27.810
I'd actually met his wife Eden
once, a number of years before.

00:16:27.810 --> 00:16:31.140
But Brad spends a good
chunk of his year in London

00:16:31.140 --> 00:16:32.790
because he's a
seminary professor

00:16:32.790 --> 00:16:34.860
at a seminary in London.

00:16:34.860 --> 00:16:38.850
And so he and I had always
been passing but hadn't met.

00:16:38.850 --> 00:16:41.700
And I'm thinking, I don't even
know if he's on the continent,

00:16:41.700 --> 00:16:45.407
but I'll send him an email and
see if he happens to be around.

00:16:45.407 --> 00:16:47.490
So I send him an email
telling him what I'm doing,

00:16:47.490 --> 00:16:49.120
coming up Wednesday.

00:16:49.120 --> 00:16:50.790
Do you happen to be in town?

00:16:50.790 --> 00:16:53.070
I immediately get an email back.

00:16:53.070 --> 00:16:55.287
Can I come pick you
up at the airport?

00:16:55.287 --> 00:16:57.120
He said, we'll spend
the whole day together,

00:16:57.120 --> 00:16:59.840
we'll have supper with Eden,
and then I'll drop you off

00:16:59.840 --> 00:17:02.010
in Chilliwack at your hotel.

00:17:02.010 --> 00:17:03.150
Great.

00:17:03.150 --> 00:17:04.440
So I called transport.

00:17:04.440 --> 00:17:07.000
They're thrilled because it
saves them five hours round

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:09.510
trip, and it's great.

00:17:09.510 --> 00:17:11.940
So it's all set.

00:17:11.940 --> 00:17:15.599
Well, 10 minutes later I
get another email from Brad.

00:17:15.599 --> 00:17:19.170
This time it's got a
photo attached to it,

00:17:19.170 --> 00:17:21.119
and it's got a picture of Brad.

00:17:21.119 --> 00:17:22.920
Because I'd seen
pictures of him.

00:17:22.920 --> 00:17:25.319
And there's another
guy next to him,

00:17:25.319 --> 00:17:28.590
and they're in the
middle of the woods.

00:17:28.590 --> 00:17:35.200
And Brad says, hey, Paul,
while we were emailing,

00:17:35.200 --> 00:17:37.870
one of my long-life
best friends Dwight

00:17:37.870 --> 00:17:39.910
and I were walking in the woods.

00:17:39.910 --> 00:17:44.350
Dwight and his wife Laurie
have a cabin summer cottage

00:17:44.350 --> 00:17:47.390
up at Cultus Lake.

00:17:47.390 --> 00:17:50.410
And we are spending
a few days with them.

00:17:50.410 --> 00:17:53.790
And while we were
emailing, Dwight and I--

00:17:53.790 --> 00:17:56.830
and he says, Dwight, by
the way, is a business guy.

00:17:56.830 --> 00:18:00.700
His wife Laurie is a
spiritual formations director.

00:18:00.700 --> 00:18:03.340
But Dwight is the first person
who told me about "The Shack"

00:18:03.340 --> 00:18:06.720
in 2008 and gave
me my first copy.

00:18:06.720 --> 00:18:10.510
But we're walking in the
woods, and look, next to them

00:18:10.510 --> 00:18:14.650
is a big arrow that's
green or yellow--

00:18:14.650 --> 00:18:16.687
I can't remember what
the color is supposed

00:18:16.687 --> 00:18:17.770
to be in British Columbia.

00:18:17.770 --> 00:18:21.650
But it says "The Shack."

00:18:21.650 --> 00:18:23.890
There's a set location
two and a half blocks away

00:18:23.890 --> 00:18:26.346
from Dwight's house, and
he didn't even know it.

00:18:26.346 --> 00:18:28.720
And as they're walking in the
woods, as he's emailing me,

00:18:28.720 --> 00:18:30.640
they run right into it.

00:18:30.640 --> 00:18:34.120
And it's like, look,
how cool is this.

00:18:34.120 --> 00:18:36.620
So I'm going, like,
this is great.

00:18:36.620 --> 00:18:38.440
And then he sends
me a second email

00:18:38.440 --> 00:18:40.360
right on the heels
of that one and says,

00:18:40.360 --> 00:18:41.920
I don't know if
it would work out

00:18:41.920 --> 00:18:44.110
because I don't know
where you're going to be.

00:18:44.110 --> 00:18:45.390
Because I don't know.

00:18:45.390 --> 00:18:47.650
It could be at any one of
these multiple locations

00:18:47.650 --> 00:18:52.020
for the set sites, and I don't
know what they're shooting.

00:18:52.020 --> 00:18:55.570
So he says, if
there's any way, I

00:18:55.570 --> 00:18:57.600
think it would be
really important if you

00:18:57.600 --> 00:19:01.590
could find even 10 minutes to
spend with Dwight and Laurie.

00:19:01.590 --> 00:19:04.440
Your book had a massive
impact in their lives.

00:19:04.440 --> 00:19:07.230
About three years ago the
youngest of their children,

00:19:07.230 --> 00:19:11.060
16 years old, took her own
life in the middle of the woods

00:19:11.060 --> 00:19:12.830
in a tree house.

00:19:12.830 --> 00:19:17.222
And Dwight's stuck and
Laurie is completely stuck.

00:19:17.222 --> 00:19:18.930
And Dwight believes
that if he could just

00:19:18.930 --> 00:19:20.820
read "The Shack" again,
he could get unstuck,

00:19:20.820 --> 00:19:23.250
but he can't get
past chapter one.

00:19:23.250 --> 00:19:29.650
And Laurie is so angry
because her daughter is dead.

00:19:29.650 --> 00:19:34.000
Her daughter is dead, and she
is furious, furious at God.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:36.100
And she can't get past this.

00:19:36.100 --> 00:19:40.750
And they're lost, so even if
you could spend 10 minutes.

00:19:40.750 --> 00:19:43.004
And I am like, [GASP].

00:19:43.004 --> 00:19:44.920
And I email back and
say, we'll figure it out.

00:19:44.920 --> 00:19:47.450
Even if I have to spend
an extra day or something,

00:19:47.450 --> 00:19:48.970
we'll figure it out.

00:19:48.970 --> 00:19:53.390
So I fly up on Wednesday.

00:19:53.390 --> 00:19:54.350
Brad picks me up.

00:19:54.350 --> 00:19:57.739
It's like meeting a
long-lost brother.

00:19:57.739 --> 00:19:59.780
You know those relationships
where the first time

00:19:59.780 --> 00:20:03.040
you meet it's like,
it's fully on?

00:20:03.040 --> 00:20:06.190
I mean, it's like,
where have you been?

00:20:06.190 --> 00:20:07.030
So it was like that.

00:20:07.030 --> 00:20:09.250
We had supper with Eden,
and then Brad drops me off.

00:20:09.250 --> 00:20:11.170
And I told him, I
said, I'll let you

00:20:11.170 --> 00:20:17.390
know when I find out where I'm
going, and we'll figure it out.

00:20:17.390 --> 00:20:21.040
And so I don't get a call
sheet until 11:30 that night.

00:20:21.040 --> 00:20:23.620
And it says, we're picking
you up at 9:30 in the morning

00:20:23.620 --> 00:20:26.980
and taking you to
Cultus Lake, the site

00:20:26.980 --> 00:20:28.829
location on Cultus Lake.

00:20:28.829 --> 00:20:31.120
So I'm going to end up being
two and a half blocks away

00:20:31.120 --> 00:20:32.776
from their little
summer cottage.

00:20:32.776 --> 00:20:35.840
And I'm going, like,
OK, that's cool.

00:20:35.840 --> 00:20:39.250
So I get up there in the
morning and I'm texting Brad.

00:20:39.250 --> 00:20:41.200
And he's saying, we're here.

00:20:41.200 --> 00:20:42.940
We're 2 and 1/2 blocks away.

00:20:42.940 --> 00:20:44.855
So we'll have food ready
for you any time you

00:20:44.855 --> 00:20:45.730
want to take a break.

00:20:45.730 --> 00:20:48.900
You just let us know, and we'll
meet you down the waterfront.

00:20:48.900 --> 00:20:53.010
And even if you can
spend 10 minutes.

00:20:53.010 --> 00:20:56.930
So I walk over to Gil
and Lonnie Netter--

00:20:56.930 --> 00:20:58.920
Lonnie is Gil's wife--

00:20:58.920 --> 00:21:02.510
and Stuart Hazeldine,
who is the producer.

00:21:02.510 --> 00:21:05.910
And they're standing,
talking to each other.

00:21:05.910 --> 00:21:08.810
And I walk over to them because
I had just gotten there.

00:21:08.810 --> 00:21:10.730
And one of the reasons
that they wanted

00:21:10.730 --> 00:21:12.440
me to come to this
site location is this

00:21:12.440 --> 00:21:14.690
is where they built the shack.

00:21:14.690 --> 00:21:16.550
And they built it
three different times,

00:21:16.550 --> 00:21:18.410
but it's all on the same site.

00:21:18.410 --> 00:21:20.630
And they wanted me to see it.

00:21:20.630 --> 00:21:26.030
Plus Octavia was there, Aviv
was there, and Sumi was there,

00:21:26.030 --> 00:21:27.750
and I hadn't met them.

00:21:27.750 --> 00:21:34.500
And so when I had gotten that
email, after my little nudge

00:21:34.500 --> 00:21:38.370
to contact Brad, and he had
told me about Dwight and Laurie,

00:21:38.370 --> 00:21:44.260
I sent Gil and Lonnie
Netter and Stuart the email.

00:21:44.260 --> 00:21:49.360
And I said, here
is another story

00:21:49.360 --> 00:21:53.140
that pertains to the movie
that you guys are working on,

00:21:53.140 --> 00:21:55.450
just so you know.

00:21:55.450 --> 00:21:57.770
Well, I walk over to
them and I say, hey,

00:21:57.770 --> 00:22:00.220
you know that email
that I just sent you

00:22:00.220 --> 00:22:03.250
about Dwight and Laurie Martin?

00:22:03.250 --> 00:22:06.130
Would there be any possibility
that my four friends could

00:22:06.130 --> 00:22:08.860
come on the set for the day?

00:22:08.860 --> 00:22:12.790
And not only did they say
yes, they said absolutely.

00:22:12.790 --> 00:22:14.650
And 20 minutes later,
down the waterfront,

00:22:14.650 --> 00:22:17.170
comes Brad, Eden,
Dwight, and Laurie.

00:22:17.170 --> 00:22:20.110
And they get embraced
into this community

00:22:20.110 --> 00:22:22.630
that is creating this movie.

00:22:22.630 --> 00:22:24.970
We don't know what
they're shooting that day.

00:22:24.970 --> 00:22:27.870
We're just thrilled to be there.

00:22:27.870 --> 00:22:34.561
So when they shoot a movie,
especially outside shots,

00:22:34.561 --> 00:22:37.060
you can't get close enough to
actually hear what's going on.

00:22:37.060 --> 00:22:38.560
Everything's miked up.

00:22:38.560 --> 00:22:41.980
And you can watch it at
a distance if you want,

00:22:41.980 --> 00:22:43.960
but they have what's
called a video village,

00:22:43.960 --> 00:22:45.640
which is just a big tent.

00:22:45.640 --> 00:22:46.622
And in that tent--

00:22:46.622 --> 00:22:48.580
it's set up for the
producer and the director--

00:22:48.580 --> 00:22:52.390
and they've got huge screens,
like five times bigger

00:22:52.390 --> 00:22:54.380
than those.

00:22:54.380 --> 00:22:56.500
And then they've
got headphones so

00:22:56.500 --> 00:22:58.840
that the producer and the
director can actually hear.

00:22:58.840 --> 00:23:00.340
And whatever they're
going to shoot,

00:23:00.340 --> 00:23:02.048
they're going to shoot
it multiple times.

00:23:02.048 --> 00:23:03.670
They had one shot
that they wanted

00:23:03.670 --> 00:23:06.040
to do all morning,
two and a half hours,

00:23:06.040 --> 00:23:09.520
one shot in the afternoon,
and one shot in the evening.

00:23:09.520 --> 00:23:13.000
So we still don't know
what they're shooting.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:15.220
They had five
chairs for us right

00:23:15.220 --> 00:23:18.547
in front of the monitors with
headphones so we could hear.

00:23:18.547 --> 00:23:20.380
And they're going to
shoot it over and over,

00:23:20.380 --> 00:23:22.330
because they want to get
different camera angles.

00:23:22.330 --> 00:23:24.621
They want to get different
expressions from the actors,

00:23:24.621 --> 00:23:25.600
whatever.

00:23:25.600 --> 00:23:27.340
So we sit down, put
our headphones on,

00:23:27.340 --> 00:23:30.670
and this is the first
scene that we see.

00:23:30.670 --> 00:23:34.090
It is the one where
Mackenzie has spent

00:23:34.090 --> 00:23:36.610
the night having nightmares.

00:23:36.610 --> 00:23:39.820
And he comes out on the
porch for breakfast,

00:23:39.820 --> 00:23:41.950
and Papa's got
breakfast for him.

00:23:41.950 --> 00:23:47.470
And you can see that he's just
struggled with these nightmares

00:23:47.470 --> 00:23:49.282
about the loss of his daughter.

00:23:49.282 --> 00:23:49.990
And he comes out.

00:23:49.990 --> 00:23:51.448
And this is the
one, if you've seen

00:23:51.448 --> 00:23:54.620
the movie, where Papa starts
the conversation with,

00:23:54.620 --> 00:23:57.020
you like Neil Young?

00:23:57.020 --> 00:24:00.010
I'm especially fond of him.

00:24:00.010 --> 00:24:04.271
And in the original, in the
book, it's Bruce Cockburn,

00:24:04.271 --> 00:24:06.020
but we couldn't get
the rights fast enough

00:24:06.020 --> 00:24:08.390
to get Bruce Cockburn's
name in there.

00:24:08.390 --> 00:24:10.216
But Neil said yes.

00:24:10.216 --> 00:24:11.840
And I like Neil, too,
just so you know.

00:24:14.540 --> 00:24:16.310
But that's how the
conversation starts.

00:24:16.310 --> 00:24:21.380
And Mackenzie goes and sits
down and doesn't touch anything,

00:24:21.380 --> 00:24:25.080
and they start a conversation.

00:24:25.080 --> 00:24:33.510
And at one point, Papa says
to Mackenzie, Mackenzie,

00:24:33.510 --> 00:24:37.110
the great flaw, the
fundamental flaw in your life,

00:24:37.110 --> 00:24:40.880
is that you don't
believe that I'm good.

00:24:40.880 --> 00:24:43.090
I am.

00:24:43.090 --> 00:24:46.480
And I'm at work in your
life for good in what

00:24:46.480 --> 00:24:48.950
you consider to be a mess.

00:24:48.950 --> 00:24:51.150
But until you believe
that I'm good,

00:24:51.150 --> 00:24:54.820
you're never going to
be able to trust me.

00:24:54.820 --> 00:24:57.430
And he looks at
her with this fury,

00:24:57.430 --> 00:25:02.080
and he smashes the plate
out in front of him.

00:25:02.080 --> 00:25:05.350
And he goes, why would
I ever trust you?

00:25:05.350 --> 00:25:08.050
My daughter is dead.

00:25:08.050 --> 00:25:09.000
Smash.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:10.630
And nothing you can
say will change it.

00:25:10.630 --> 00:25:12.680
Walk away.

00:25:12.680 --> 00:25:15.780
And we're like, [GASP].

00:25:15.780 --> 00:25:20.380
And I look over at Dwight and
Laurie, and they're in shock.

00:25:20.380 --> 00:25:22.670
And then we watch it again.

00:25:22.670 --> 00:25:24.490
And then we watch it again.

00:25:24.490 --> 00:25:25.900
Why would I ever trust you?

00:25:25.900 --> 00:25:27.250
My daughter is dead.

00:25:27.250 --> 00:25:30.800
Mackenzie, until you
believe that I'm good,

00:25:30.800 --> 00:25:32.920
you're never going to
be able to trust me--

00:25:32.920 --> 00:25:35.350
the fundamental
flaw in your life.

00:25:35.350 --> 00:25:37.600
Why would I ever trust you?

00:25:37.600 --> 00:25:39.000
My daughter is dead.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:40.500
And by the third
time through, we're

00:25:40.500 --> 00:25:45.950
bawling, because this is
right at the core of where

00:25:45.950 --> 00:25:48.780
Dwight and Laurie are stuck.

00:25:48.780 --> 00:25:53.040
Well, for two hours,
right, we're watching this.

00:25:53.040 --> 00:25:54.210
We take a break.

00:25:54.210 --> 00:25:58.560
Octavia comes over and
just hugs on everybody.

00:25:58.560 --> 00:26:01.060
So does Sumi and so does Aviv.

00:26:01.060 --> 00:26:02.780
Aviv plays Jesus.

00:26:02.780 --> 00:26:04.310
Aviv is a Jew.

00:26:04.310 --> 00:26:05.610
Can you imagine?

00:26:05.610 --> 00:26:08.580
A Jew playing Jesus?

00:26:08.580 --> 00:26:10.350
Who would have thought?

00:26:10.350 --> 00:26:11.700
You have to understand.

00:26:11.700 --> 00:26:15.289
I get emails from my people,
evangelical fundamentalists,

00:26:15.289 --> 00:26:16.830
and I've gotten at
least five of them

00:26:16.830 --> 00:26:19.693
go like, how dare you make
Jesus a Middle Easterner?

00:26:25.620 --> 00:26:29.190
What, you've only seen
him in the movies or what?

00:26:29.190 --> 00:26:30.570
I checked with the Jews--

00:26:30.570 --> 00:26:31.830
I mean, the Jewish consulate.

00:26:31.830 --> 00:26:32.530
They are Jews.

00:26:32.530 --> 00:26:34.940
They're Middle Easterners.

00:26:34.940 --> 00:26:38.770
But they come over and
they just love on us.

00:26:38.770 --> 00:26:42.390
Well, in the afternoon, we
sit down for the second shot.

00:26:42.390 --> 00:26:44.580
And it's the one where Papa
is talking to Mackenzie.

00:26:44.580 --> 00:26:46.440
Mackenzie is
sitting on the porch

00:26:46.440 --> 00:26:48.806
and they're talking
about a bird.

00:26:48.806 --> 00:26:50.180
And Papa says,
you know, pain has

00:26:50.180 --> 00:26:53.660
a way of clipping your
wings so that you forget

00:26:53.660 --> 00:26:55.250
you were ever created to fly.

00:26:55.250 --> 00:26:59.150
You're looking through this
little knothole of your loss

00:26:59.150 --> 00:27:01.910
and defining the whole universe.

00:27:01.910 --> 00:27:02.690
And we're gone.

00:27:02.690 --> 00:27:08.820
The first shot we're
just, like, toast.

00:27:08.820 --> 00:27:11.290
And it was two
more hours of that.

00:27:11.290 --> 00:27:14.620
At the end of that day,
we're hugging goodbye.

00:27:14.620 --> 00:27:17.404
And Laurie says,
you have no idea.

00:27:17.404 --> 00:27:18.070
And that's true.

00:27:18.070 --> 00:27:18.970
I don't.

00:27:18.970 --> 00:27:22.540
I don't know how the ripples
go and how the layers are.

00:27:22.540 --> 00:27:24.600
I don't know.

00:27:24.600 --> 00:27:26.640
But to be able to participate
in the holy ground

00:27:26.640 --> 00:27:27.765
of other people's stories--

00:27:31.240 --> 00:27:32.530
how incredible is that?

00:27:32.530 --> 00:27:35.720
And we all do it.

00:27:35.720 --> 00:27:40.120
We just don't spend enough time
staying present to realize it.

00:27:40.120 --> 00:27:41.680
Our choices actually matter.

00:27:41.680 --> 00:27:44.530
Our participation
actually matters.

00:27:44.530 --> 00:27:46.490
And that's just
one of the stories

00:27:46.490 --> 00:27:52.930
that just happened inside the
context of a movie being shot.

00:27:52.930 --> 00:27:56.660
The book has done it,
too, all over the world.

00:27:56.660 --> 00:27:58.730
I made 15 copies that
did everything I ever

00:27:58.730 --> 00:28:01.330
wanted it to do, and
it's the number two

00:28:01.330 --> 00:28:04.709
book in the history of Brazil.

00:28:04.709 --> 00:28:06.250
You know who my
distributor in Brazil

00:28:06.250 --> 00:28:07.720
is, my number one distributor?

00:28:07.720 --> 00:28:10.780
You would not believe
this, but you will.

00:28:10.780 --> 00:28:12.070
But it's just so--

00:28:12.070 --> 00:28:13.300
you wouldn't think of it.

00:28:13.300 --> 00:28:16.030
And that is, there's
no distribution system,

00:28:16.030 --> 00:28:20.270
and Brazil is the same size as
the continental United States.

00:28:20.270 --> 00:28:22.750
It's just that American
cartographers used

00:28:22.750 --> 00:28:24.280
to make all the
maps, so they always

00:28:24.280 --> 00:28:27.860
made America look the biggest.

00:28:27.860 --> 00:28:31.930
But the only reason the US
has more land area than Brazil

00:28:31.930 --> 00:28:33.970
is because of Alaska.

00:28:33.970 --> 00:28:37.240
But other than that,
it's the same size.

00:28:37.240 --> 00:28:40.390
They have no distribution
system, no mass delivery

00:28:40.390 --> 00:28:42.040
freight system on the ground.

00:28:42.040 --> 00:28:46.510
And my number one distributor,
who sold over 3 million copies

00:28:46.510 --> 00:28:48.130
by themselves, is Avon.

00:28:50.650 --> 00:28:55.486
Avon-- door-to-door
cosmetics and books.

00:28:55.486 --> 00:28:56.290
AUDIENCE: Crazy.

00:28:56.290 --> 00:28:58.030
WILLIAM PAUL YOUNG: It is crazy.

00:28:58.030 --> 00:29:00.382
And then Croatia
dubbed "The Shack"

00:29:00.382 --> 00:29:02.590
their book of the decade,
and the Ministry of Culture

00:29:02.590 --> 00:29:05.170
asked me almost
two years ago now

00:29:05.170 --> 00:29:06.870
to come speak to the country.

00:29:06.870 --> 00:29:07.840
And I did that.

00:29:07.840 --> 00:29:09.160
I was cleaning toilets.

00:29:09.160 --> 00:29:11.440
You understand how bizarre
this whole thing is?

00:29:11.440 --> 00:29:15.340
This is totally
God's sense of humor.

00:29:15.340 --> 00:29:20.140
And so it has been
an unanticipated

00:29:20.140 --> 00:29:26.620
and unprecedented, in a lot of
respects, adventure or journey,

00:29:26.620 --> 00:29:29.740
complete with its
own set of crosses.

00:29:29.740 --> 00:29:32.530
But it's been fantastic.

00:29:32.530 --> 00:29:34.309
I'm thrilled to be a part of it.

00:29:34.309 --> 00:29:36.850
Kim would tell you, and my kids
would tell you and my friends

00:29:36.850 --> 00:29:40.000
would tell you, that if all
this-- notoriety, platform,

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:41.050
all this stuff--

00:29:41.050 --> 00:29:43.540
if it all went away
tomorrow, I'd be fine.

00:29:43.540 --> 00:29:44.690
I'd be great.

00:29:44.690 --> 00:29:47.320
I was great before this.

00:29:47.320 --> 00:29:50.680
I finally was comfortable
inside my own skin,

00:29:50.680 --> 00:29:52.180
and that took a lot of time.

00:29:52.180 --> 00:29:56.830
It took all of 50 years
to get to that place.

00:29:56.830 --> 00:29:58.910
So that's the big
bird's eye view.

